From: lxh <lmhtq1991@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 28 May 2026 16:30:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] Phase C-6 fix #16: set bit 0 on entry_point before BLR

Mirror of patch 0092 but for the Java entry_point cap (c_rarg4),
not the call_stub cap itself. Per ARM ARM §2.10 RZTMWK, BLR sets
PSTATE.C64 from the target cap's bit 0. The Java entry_point
(interpreter/JIT entry) is C64 code, so the BLR target must have
bit 0 set to enter C64 mode.

HotSpot's stub pointers are byte-aligned (bit 0 = 0). cap-ADD #1
preserves tag and sets bit 0 in the address (which on BLR becomes
the mode bit, with actual fetch address having bit 0 cleared
automatically — same semantics as ARM/Thumb interworking on
classic AArch32).

Encoding cap-ADD c4, c4, #1: 0x02000484 (verified vs clang).

After this patch, call_stub correctly enters Java entry_point in
C64 mode. But the JVM still SIGILLs — now inside the template
interpreter itself, which is the next big porting target (~256
bytecode entry stubs, each potentially having the same integer-
vs-cap encoding issue as call_stub had).

C-6 cascade resolved for call_stub. Layer 17+ work shifts to
template interpreter (separate stubGenerator file).

diff --git a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/stubGenerator_aarch64.cpp b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/stubGenerator_aarch64.cpp
--- a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/stubGenerator_aarch64.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/stubGenerator_aarch64.cpp
@@ -323,6 +323,15 @@
     BLOCK_COMMENT("call Java function");
     __ mov(r13, sp);
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+    // C-6 fix #16: set bit 0 on entry_point cap so BLR enters C64
+    // mode (mirror of patch 0092 for call_stub's own entry; same rule
+    // RZTMWK from ARM ARM §2.10). cap-ADD c4, c4, #1 preserves tag,
+    // adds 1 to address (which then becomes the mode bit on BLR).
+    // Encoding: 0x02000000 | (imm12<<10) | (Rn<<5) | Rd
+    // For c4: 0x02000000 | (1<<10) | (4<<5) | 4 = 0x02000484
+    __ emit_int32(0x02000000U | (1U << 10) | (4U << 5) | 4U);
+#endif
     __ blr(c_rarg4);
